From cou.: 5 Fig. 1 provides a schematic overview of the Hamiltonian identification procedure utilized in this work. In the experimental component (A), a set of K control fields εk(t), k = 1,…,K are generated. Field noise, denoted ηεk, may enter each experiment; here εk(t) + ηεk is meant to accommodate any form of noise (e.g., additive or multiplicative). The fields εk(t), k = 1,…,K separately interact with the system through the Hamiltonian H and produce a corresponding set of observables, denoted Ok(T), for measurement at terminal time T. Uncertainly in the kth measurement is accounted for by the noise ηOk. In the inversion component (B), a trial Hamiltonian is chosen. The input fields from (A) are used to compute Õk(T) based on , corresponding to the same type of measurement from (A). The inversion cost function J is defined,
From Soup: 5 Fig. 1 provides a schematic overview of the Hamiltonian identification procedure utilized in this work. In the experimental component (A), a set of K control fields ε k ( t ), k = 1,…, K are generated. Field noise, denoted η ε k , may enter each experiment; here ε k ( t ) + η ε k is meant to accommodate any form of noise ( e.g. , additive or multiplicative). The fields ε k ( t ), k = 1,…, K separately interact with the system through the Hamiltonian H and produce a corresponding set of observables, denoted O k ( T ), for measurement at terminal time T . Uncertainly in the k th measurement is accounted for by the noise η O k . In the inversion component (B), a trial Hamiltonian is chosen. The input fields from (A) are used to compute Õ k ( T ) based on , corresponding to the same type of measurement from (A). The inversion cost function J is defined,
