From cou.: 98 The simulations presented below are meant to be an initial foray into understanding the Hamiltonian inversion landscape. The prior work27 considered the problem of identifying a nondegenerate quantum system's real symmetric transition dipole matrix, where H0 is known and the diagonal elements of the dipole matrix are also known to be zero. The analytical results showed local inversion landscape convexity about the true Hamiltonian when (1) no noise was present, (2) a sufficiently large number of experimental measurements were utilized, (3) the trial Hamiltonians lie within some neighborhood around the true Hamiltonian, and (4) the time duration of the applied electromagnetic field, T, was arbitrarily large. These issues are selectively addressed below. The simulations also aim to illustrate the ability of a simple gradient search algorithm (D-MORPH) to correctly identify a quantum system's Hamiltonian when a modest number of experiments with reasonable levels of noise-ridden data are incorporated into an inversion procedure.
