From Soup: 122 To explore the impact of increasing the amount of data used for inversion, Fig. 6 shows results from 40 simulations where (a) trial dipole matrices were taken from a domain 50–75% away from eqn (11) , (b) the incorporated noise was on the order of 2–5%, and (c) K = 30 experimental measurements were used compared to the 18 utilized in the previous sets of simulations. Conditions (a) and (b) are the same as the illustrations in Fig. 5 . Fig. 6A displays J versus M μ , and again two regions are observed: one region with J > 0.0021 and one with J < 0.0021. The latter set comprised 26 out of the 40 runs. Fig. 6B shows the distribution of identified matrix elements for all 40 runs; the mean extracted dipole values are (1,2) = 1.42, (1,3) = 1.32, (1,4) = 0.99, (2,3) = 2.00, (2,4) = 0.51, (3,4) = 1.57 with standard deviations are 0.44, 0.72, 0.25, 0.67, 0.17, and 0.54, respectively. Fig. 6C zooms in on Fig. 6A to consider the 26 cases where J < 0.0021, and Fig. 6D displays the associated matrix element values. The mean extracted dipole values are (1,2) = 1.47, (1,3) = 1.23, (1,4) = 0.96, (2,3) = 1.76, (2,4) = 0.54, (3,4) = 1.42 and the distribution is much smaller compared to 6B, with standard deviations decreasing to 0.11, 0.044, 0.077, 0.11, 0.049, and 0.068, respectively. Overall the convergence to μ ( cf. , eqn (11) ) is improved using more experiments compared to Fig. 5 , though importantly K = 30 still constitutes a very modest amount of data to consider for inversion.
